oung working-class women who have little cultural capital to enable class mobility; to the fact that analyses of class too often remain insufficiently transformed by feminist, ethnic, and queer studies; and to the failure of some feminist theory itself to theorize women as class subjects.Women without Class makes a case for analytical and political attention to class, but not at the expense of attention to other social formations.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChildren, WhitezCaliforniazSan Francisco Bay AreaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aHigh school studentszCaliforniaxSocial conditions. 0aMexican American studentszCaliforniaxSocial conditions. 0aMexican American teenage girlsxRace identityzCalifornia. 0aMexican American teenage girlszCaliforniaxSocial conditions. 0aSocial classeszCalifornia. 0aTeenage girls, WhitexRace identityzCalifornia. 0aTeenage girls, WhitezCaliforniaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aanthropologist.  acalifornia women.  acentral valley.  aclass performance.  aclass theory.  acolor.  acoming of age.  acontemporary movement.  acultural reference.  acultural theory.  aethnicity.  agender.  ahistorical context.  aincome disparity.  amexican-american women.  asexuality.  asociologists.  atheorists.  awhite girls.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028001440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095724440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520957244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520957244/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY